{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516044","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516044"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:38:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:38:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12552"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12552","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12552"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.08,0.17,0.51,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5051"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113346"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5051"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12552"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95367"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1564"},{"type":"tags","id":"5613"},{"type":"tags","id":"5614"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8402"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8413"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8507"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15427"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113346"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman has a spinal anaesthetic for her caesarean section. The caesarean section is performed due to fetal distress and her baby is delivered safely with an uneventful procedure. The spinal anaesthetic is administered without any difficulty. The day after the surgery, she develops a severe headache which is worse when she stands or coughs and improves with lying down. She has taken paracetamol which has had no effect on her pain. She describes the pain as debilitating as she is unable to ambulate and is finding it very difficult to feed and care for her baby. On physical examination, her blood pressure is 130/85 mmHg, pulse 77/min, temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, and there are no neurological deficits or meningism.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate definitive treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous fluids","Intravenous caffeine","Intravenous corticosteroids","Epidural blood patch","Oral oxycodone"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has \u003Cstrong\u003Epost-dural puncture headache (PDPH)\u003C/strong\u003E, a common complication of spinal anaesthesia, caused by cerebrospinal fluid leakage through the hole in the dura. The headache typically presents within 24-72 hours after the procedure. It is often described as a severe, throbbing headache that worsens when the patient is sitting or standing and improves when lying down. The diagnosis of PDPH is based on the characteristic symptoms of pain exacerbations with standing, coughing and relief by laying down, in conjunction with a history of recent spinal cord instrumentation (spinal anaesthetic, lumbar puncture etc). The diagnosis is usually clinical, and confirmed by ruling out other potential causes of headache.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are several treatment options for PDPH, ranging from conservative measures to more invasive interventions. Conservative measures include bed rest, increased fluid intake, simple oral analgesia and oral or intravenous caffeine. These measures can provide symptomatic relief and are preferred in mild cases as PDPH is often self-limiting with symptoms that will resolve in a week. However, in more severe and debilitating cases, more rapid and definitive treatment can be utilised.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpidural blood patch (EBP)\u003C/strong\u003E is an effective treatment for PDPH, with reported success rates of up to 90%. The procedure involves injecting a small amount of the patient\u0027s blood into the epidural space at the puncture site. The blood acts as a sealant, closing the hole and restoring normal cerebrospinal fluid pressure. EBP is generally considered safe and has a low risk of complications, such as infection or nerve damage. It would be preferred in this patient because her headache is severe and significantly interfering with the care of her baby, necessitating immediate management steps.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous fluids\u003C/strong\u003E may help alleviate the headache by increasing intracranial pressure and maintaining adequate hydration, in the situation that oral fluids were not possible. However, whilst it may form part of supportive management for a mild headache, it is not a definitive treatment for post-dural puncture headache.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECaffeine-containing medications, such as coffee/tea or\u003Cstrong\u003E intravenous caffeine\u003C/strong\u003E can help alleviate the headache by constricting the blood vessels and decreasing cerebral blood flow. This will commonly form part of the management of a mild PDPH, however the effectiveness of caffeine in PDPH can be variable and in severe cases such as this more definitive management is preferred. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous corticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E are not recommended for the treatment of PDPH, as there is no evidence to support their efficacy in this condition. Moreover, the use of corticosteroids carries a risk of significant side effects, including hyperglycemia, hypertension, and immune suppression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral oxycodone \u003C/strong\u003Ewould not be an appropriate choice for this presentation, as opiate analgesia is not recommended for PDPH and would only be a bridge to definitive and targeted therapy.\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Epidural blood patch (EBP) is the definitive treatment option for post-dural puncture headache (PDPH).","Post-dural puncture headache (PDPH) is a common complication following spinal anaesthesia.","Epidural blood patch (EBP) is usually preferred in postnatally when the headache interferes with the care of the baby."],"references":["Basurto Ona X, Osorio D, Bonfill Cosp X. Drug therapy for treating post-dural puncture headache. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2015 Jul 15;2015(7):CD007887.","Mart\u00ednez B, Canser E, Alonso A, Alonso E, Gredilla E, D\u00edez J, Gilsanz F. Postdural Puncture Headache and Epidural Blood Patch in a Large Obstetric Anaesthesia Population. Asian J Anesthesiol. 2018 Mar;56(1):23-32. doi: 10.6859/aja.201803_56(1).0003. PMID: 29847969.","Vallejo MC, Zakowski MI. Post-dural puncture headache diagnosis and management. Best Pract Res Clin Anaesthesiol. 2022 May;36(1):179-189. doi: 10.1016/j.bpa.2022.01.002. Epub 2022 Jan 25. PMID: 35659954."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95367"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12552"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95367"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-11T17:38:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-11T17:38:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5051"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113346"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,